Prediction of patient with liver desease¶

Introduction¶

The liver is an organ about the size of a football. It sits just the rib cage on the right side of the abdomen. It is one on the most important organs of our body and it is responsible for digesting food and ridding our body of toxic substances. Such role of filtering makes it vulnerable to the toxins it processes. Too many toxins can overwhelm liver's resources and ability to function. This can happen temporarily or over a long period of time.

Usually, liver diseases are chronic conditions that do progressive damage to the organ over time. Among common causes we find genetic inheritance, viruses, alcohol abuse and obesity. The liver has a great regenerative power but conditions that damage it can lead to scarring (cirrhosis), which can lead to liver failure.

Every year in Italy, approximately 15 thousands patients die of cirrhosis and about 6 thounsands die of liver cancer. It is important to identify possible liver infections at an early stage in order to adopt treatments that may give the liver time to heal.

Research question¶

Given the criticity of a condition like liver disease, it is important to being able to identify potential infections and dangers at an early stage. This is the only way to aid the organ in the purging of the infection and the starting of the healing process.

Machine Learning can be of great help, allowing to solve the problem via automation of the analysis of the patient. In this project I will try to create and validate a model that predicts whether a patient suffers of liver disease or not.

As mentioned in the documentation of the dataset that I choose, previous researches on this field have pointed out how there is a difference in the effect of predicting diseases in case of male and female patients. Another point of this project is to try to verify this behavior with the mentioned dataset.

Dataset¶

The dataset that I'm going to use for this project is ILPD (Indian Liver Patient Dataset) and it can be found here. It comprises 583 patient records collected from the NorthEast of Andhra Pradesh, India. Variables contains information about several biochemical markers and a target variable that indicates if the patient suffers from live desease.

One limitation of the dateset may be that the target variable is a bit imbalanced: 416 patients with disease and 167 patients without disease. This can be managed during validation phase. On the other hand, the dataset seems to have no missing data. We will verify this later.

Let's quickly explore the variables of the dataset:

  • Age: Age of the patient [years]
  • Gender: Gender of the patient [Male/Female]
  • TB: Total Bilirubin [mg/dL]
  • DB: Direct Bilirubin [mg/dL]
  • Alkphos: Alkaline Phosphotase [unit/L]
  • Sgpt: Alamine Aminotransferase [unit/L]
  • Sgot: Aspartate Aminotransferase [unit/L]
  • TP: Total Proteins [g/dL]
  • ALB: Albumin [g/100mL]
  • A/G Ratio: Albumin and Globulin Ratio
  • Selector: indicates if patient suffers of liver disease [1:Yes, 2:No]

All variables (except for Age, Gender, Selector) refers to components that are related either to blood or liver. They are usually tested to check, among many disease, for liver anomalies.

Actually, there are 4 missing data in A/G Ratio column. Luckily, we can resolve this issue: by domain knowledge, we know that TP (Total Protein) is approximately the sum of ALB (Albumin) and Globulin. We can retrieve Globulin amount from the two columns TP and ALB (GLB = TP - ALB) and compute the missing values of A/G Ratio (Albumin and Globulin Ratio). To be fair, this is not 100% correct because Total Protein takes into account all types of protein inside blood. However, Albumin and Globulin are found in the highest concentration so, for the sake of retreiving 4 missing values, we can rely on this simplyfication of the formula.

In [8]:
ds['A/G Ratio'] = ds['A/G Ratio'].fillna(ds['ALB']/(ds["TP"] - ds["ALB"]))

ds.insert(9, "GLB", round((1/ds["A/G Ratio"]) * ds["ALB"], 1))

For such records, the Direct Birilubin is higher than the Total Birilubin. This doesn't seem to make any sense. After some research, I found out that the presence of a monoclonal immunoglobulin falsely increased the direct, but not the total, bilirubin measurement. So for these 3 records we have a measurement error. Here's what we can do: references values for this components tell us that, generally, direct bilirubin is roughly 30% of the total birilubin. For these 3 records we can substitute the incorrect values of DB using this intuition.

In [13]:
ds["DB"].mask(ds["IB"] < 0, np.NaN, inplace=True)
ds["DB"].mask(ds["DB"].isna(), round(ds["TB"] * 0.3, 1), inplace=True)

Now let's recompute IB column.

ds["IB"] = round(ds["TB"] - ds["DB"], 1)

Outliers removal¶

One last important step of Data Preprocessing is the removal of outliers. From theory, we know that we can use Z-score for features that are normally distributed or approximately normally distributed. We are going to use the first technique for Age, TP, ALB, GLB and A/G Ratio. For all the other columns, one could think that these are just highly skewed normal distribution (in such case we would use IQR Filtering for outliers), or even log normal distribution. However, testing the variables for these distribution resulted in failed tests. For example:

In [20]:
ss.normaltest(np.log(ds["TP"]), axis=0).pvalue
Out[20]:
3.7262606972602625e-22

They don't seem to resemble any familiar distribution so it's difficult to find a good way to detect and remove outliers. In fact, using IRQ filtering on the other columns would reduce the dataset of the 70%. We proceed to remove outliers only for variables that resembles a normal distribution.

In [21]:
zscore_columns = ["Age", "TP", "ALB", "GLB", "A/G Ratio"]

for i in zscore_columns:
    
    upper_limit = ds[i].mean() + 3 * ds[i].std()
    lower_limit = ds[i].mean() - 3 * ds[i].std()
    
    ds = ds[(ds[i] <= upper_limit) & (ds[i] >= lower_limit)]

In [28]:
## This function is needed to construct a pandas.Interval starting from a String

def interval_type(s):
    """Parse interval string to Interval"""
    s = s.get_text()
    
    table = str.maketrans({'[': '(', ']': ')'})
    left_closed = s.startswith('[')
    right_closed = s.endswith(']')
    
    left, right = ast.literal_eval(s.translate(table))

    t = 'neither'
    if left_closed and right_closed:
        t = 'both'
    elif left_closed:
        t = 'left'
    elif right_closed:
        t = 'right'

    return pd.Interval(left, right, closed=t)

Despite imbalance in the number of Males and Females we can observe few things:

  • While Males suffers of Liver Disease throughout all Ages, Females that are Liver Patient are found the most between Age of 30 and 60.
  • For what regards TB, IB and DB, Males and Females present the same kind of behavior.
  • About Sgpt and Sgot variables, Males tend to have high anomaly values more that Female. Such high anomaly values always come with Liver Disease.
  • Males displays Liver Disease in a similar way for all levels of TP and ALB. On the other hand, for Females, we have ranges of ALB more affected by Liver Diseases, while for TP we have no particular behavior.

  • For A/G Ratio, we have no particular insights.

In order to come to bold conclusions we'd need a higher amount of data. However, we can observe how some indicators present the same behavior for both Genders, some other indicators presents a particular behavior for just one of the two.

Feature selection¶

Feature selection is the process of reducing the number of input variables when developing a predictive model. It is desirable to reduce the number of input variables to both reduce the computational cost of modeling and, in some cases, to improve the performance of the model. In our case, we choose to select a subset of feature, by considering the first 5 with highest correlation with Selector. We decide to do so not for a matter of high dimensionality but because, in general, the correlation scores with Selector are not astonishing (avg. correlation score = 0.15). By keeping only the features with correlation score higher that the avg, we hope to bring out the best of this dataset.

Scaling¶

First of all, since many ML algorithms are sensitive to the scale of data, we need to adopt scaling techniques on our feature . Given the characteristics of the features, we may apply different scaling techniques: for example, in our dataset we have some variables that are normally distributed and others that are not. We should use Robust Scaling for those that are not normally distributed with a strong skewness and use Standardization for those that are already normally distributed. In particular, with Robust Scaling the median is removed and data are scaled according to the quantile range. Standardization, instead, centers data around a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.

In [34]:
robust_scaler = RobustScaler()
standard_scaler = StandardScaler()

ds["TB"] = robust_scaler.fit_transform(ds[["TB"]])
ds["IB"] = robust_scaler.fit_transform(ds[["IB"]])
ds["DB"] = robust_scaler.fit_transform(ds[["DB"]])

Cross-validation procedure¶

First of all, we need to spend a couple of world for the Model Validation. We know that the simplest model evaluation procedure is to split a dataset into two parts and use one part for training a model and the second part for testing the model. As such, the parts of the dataset are named for their function, train set and test set respectively.

This is effective if our collected dataset is very large and representative of the problem. In reality, we rarely have enough data to get an unbiased estimate of performance using a train/test split evaluation of a model. It is a much better idea to split the datase in more than just 2 folds. That's why we are going to use k-fold Cross-validation to prepare our training set and test set.

However, we have to keep in mind that our dataset is imbalanced with respect to the target variable Selector. That's why simple k-fold Cross-validation is not enough. We have to use STRATIFIED k-fold Cross-validation. In this way, we are sure that the sampling of the folds will take into account the imbalance of data and will enforce the class distribution in each split of the data to match the distribution in the complete training dataset.

Here we see how the distribution is mantained for each one of the 10 splits.

In [46]:
kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=1)

for train_ix, test_ix in kfold.split(X, y):
    
    train_X, test_X = X.loc[train_ix], X.loc[test_ix]
    train_y, test_y = y.loc[train_ix], y.loc[test_ix]
    
    train_0, train_1 = len(train_y[train_y["Selector"] == 0]), len(train_y[train_y["Selector"] == 1])
    test_0, test_1 = len(test_y[test_y["Selector"] == 0]), len(test_y[test_y["Selector"] == 1])
    
    print("> Train: 0={0}, 1={1}, Test: 0={2}, 1={3}".format(train_0, train_1, test_0, test_1))

Train Test Split¶

In order to test the output of the classifier, we split the data into a training and testing set, keeping in mind once again that out data are imbalanced with respect to Selector.

In [47]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, stratify=y, test_size=0.25, random_state=27)

We define a function model_evaluation to train the model and apply it to the test set. It also shows the classification report, the precision-recall curve and the confusion matrix. To be point out, Precision-Recall curve should be used in a context where there is class imbalance. ROC generallly present an optimistic picture of the model on datasets with a class imbalance so in our case it could be deceptive and lead to incorrect interpretations of the model skill. In both curves, generally AUC is used as practical metric to compare different models.

In [48]:
# This function plots the Precision-Recall curve and computes the Area Under Curve. By default PR Curve for a No skilled classifier
# is plotted to immediately check if our model perfoms, at least better than that. In particular, a classifier with no skill is a
# classifier that always a random class or a constant class in all cases.

def my_pr_curve(model):
    
    dummy = DummyClassifier(strategy='stratified')
    dummy.fit(X_train, y_train)
    yhat = dummy.predict_proba(X_test)
    pos_probs = yhat[:, 1]  
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test, pos_probs)
    auc_score = auc(recall, precision)
    print('No Skill PR AUC: %.3f' % auc_score)
    
    yhat = model.predict_proba(X_test)
    pos_probs = yhat[:, 1]
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test, pos_probs)
    auc_score = auc(recall, precision)
    print('Model PR AUC: %.3f' % auc_score) 
    
    no_skill = len(y[y["Selector"]==1]) / len(y)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [no_skill, no_skill], linestyle='--', label='No Skill')
    plt.plot(recall, precision, marker='.', label='Model')
    plt.xlabel('Recall')
    plt.ylabel('Precision')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
In [49]:
# This function plots the ROC curve and computes the Area Under Curve of ROC curve. By default ROC curve for a Random 
# classifier is plotted to immediately check if our model performs, at least, better than that.

def my_roc(model):
    
    dummy = DummyClassifier(strategy='stratified')
    dummy.fit(X_train, y_train)
    yhat = dummy.predict_proba(X_test)
    pos_probs = yhat[:, 1]
    roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, pos_probs)
    print('No Skill ROC AUC %.3f' % roc_auc)
    
    yhat = model.predict_proba(X_test)
    pos_probs = yhat[:, 1]
    roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, pos_probs)
    print('Model ROC AUC %.3f' % roc_auc)
    
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle='--', label='No Skill')
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, pos_probs)
    
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, marker='.', label='Model')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
In [50]:
# This function applies Grid Search to find the best hyperparameters. Within Grid Search, 10-fold cross validation is used as 
# splitting strategy. By defaulf parameter refit of GridSearchCV function is set to True. This means that, in the end, the estimator 
# is refit on training data using the best found parameters on the whole dataset.

def model_evaluation(mdl, parameters, cv, scoring="accuracy"):
    
    clf = GridSearchCV(mdl,                    # model
                   param_grid = parameters,   # hyperparameters
                   scoring=scoring,           # metric for scoring
                   cv=cv)                     # number of folds
    
    clf.fit(X_train,y_train)
    
    print("Results of Training")
    print("-----------------------------------")
    print("Tuned Hyperparameters :", clf.best_params_)
    print("Accuracy :",clf.best_score_)
    print("-----------------------------------\n")
    
    model = clf.best_estimator_
    y_fit = model.predict(X_test)
    #y_scores = model.decision_function(X_test)
    
    print("Report after Predictions")
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_fit, target_names=["Without Liver Disease", "With Liver Disease"]))
    
    my_roc(model)
    my_pr_curve(model)
    
    mat = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_fit)
    sns.heatmap(mat.T, square=True, annot=True, fmt='d', cbar=False,
                xticklabels=["Without Liver Disease", "With Liver Disease"],
                yticklabels=["Without Liver Disease", "With Liver Disease"])
    plt.xlabel('true label')
    plt.ylabel('predicted label')
    
    return y_fit

Despite the high accuracy, this models perform terribly bad. As we can notice, it just predicts almost everything to be 1 (With Liver Disease). This is not the behavior we are searching or expecting, ever more so after being so cautios about taking into account imbalance in data. However, there is one thing we can try: we can add the parameter class_weight set to balanced. Doing so the model uses the values of the target to automatically adjust weights inversely proportional to class frequencies in the input data. Then, the model learns that, even if class (Without Liver Disease) is less frequent, it still needs to learn how to recognize that class. We also try other combination of weights.

Here we try F1_score as scoring modality for GridSearchCV, the harmonic mean of precision and recall. It provides a balance between precision and recall and is especially useful when the class distribution is imbalanced. However, F1_score is biased towards all, except True Negative and our goal is to improve the results by obtaining a Classifier that is not trivial and can also classifies Negative labels correctely. To address this, we use a version where the F1 score of each class label is taken and the average between the two is computed. (F1-score for negative class is the default formula with TN instead of TP.)

    'class_weight' : ['balanced', {0: 55, 1: 45}, {0: 60, 1: 40}, {0: 100, 1: 10}, {0: 70, 1: 30}]
}

result = model_evaluation(lr, parameters, cv, "f1_macro")

K-Nearest Neighbors¶

As last model, we try K-NN, particularly useful for Binary Classification, given its semplicity. When a data point is provided to the algorithm, with a given value of K, it searches for the K nearest neighbors to that data point. The nearest neighbors are found by calculating the distance between the given data point and the data points in the initial dataset. Once K nearest neighbors are identified, the KNN algorithm next determines the majority of neighbors belong to which class.

In [56]:
knn = KNeighborsClassifier()

parameters = {
    'n_neighbors': range(1,11),
    'metric': ['minkowski', 'euclidean', 'manhattan'],
    'weights': ['uniform', 'distance'],

In [57]:
def model_evaluation_ovr(model, parameters, cv, scoring="accuracy"):
    
    clf = GridSearchCV(model,                    # model
                   param_grid = parameters,   # hyperparameters
                   scoring=scoring,           # metric for scoring
                   cv=cv)                     # number of folds
    
    steps = [('over', RandomOverSampler(sampling_strategy=0.7)), ('model', clf)]
    pipeline = Pipeline(steps=steps)
    
    pipeline.fit(X_train,y_train)
    
    #print("Tuned Hyperparameters :", pipeline.best_params_)
    #print("Accuracy :",pipeline.best_score_)
    
    #model = pipeline.best_estimator_
    y_fit = pipeline.predict(X_test)
    #y_scores = pipeline.decision_function(X_test)
    
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_fit, target_names=["Without Liver Disease", "With Liver Disease"]))
    
    my_roc(pipeline)
    my_pr_curve(pipeline)
    
    mat = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_fit)
    sns.heatmap(mat.T, square=True, annot=True, fmt='d', cbar=False,
                xticklabels=["Without Liver Disease", "With Liver Disease"],
                yticklabels=["Without Liver Disease", "With Liver Disease"])
    plt.xlabel('true label')
    plt.ylabel('predicted label')

Results¶

In terms of Accuracy, the best performing models is, obviously, the Logistic Regression without class weights. As already mentioned, this is not a good result because the good accuracy here is due to datasat imbalance. If we take into account F1-score, in particular the average between F1-score for Positive label and F1-score for Negative label, we see that the best model is the Logistic Regression with class weights. For what concerns SVM, we saw how this model tend to be more correct on Negative samples but, at the same time, produces a higher number of False Negatives. False Negatives can cause many problem in a classification task of this kind. Finally, it seems that K-NN with over sampling and Logistic Regression with class weights are the two most reasonable models: they have good metric with respect to all the models and they are more balanced in the performance of both labels, with respect to SVM model.

It is then reasonable to choose one of these two last model to perform the task of predicting patients with liver disease. One can argue that the results are not fantastic but this can be attributed to the general class imbalance that the dataset present. Such issue can be eased by oversampling or class weight but still it remains a problem that makes any classification task more difficult.

Another point that can be explored with more advanced technique is the understanding of the distribution of some of the variables in this dataset. Many of the variables of this dataset were characterized by not-normal distributions. I tried to check if they were log-normal (given their highly skewed shape) but it was not the case. Maybe, the results we obtained is also determined by outliers that were not removed. However, without having insight about the distribution it is difficult to identy them in a proper general way, without losing relevant data.

It can be interesting to resolve this classification problem once again with more data available, to finally understand if features that are provided are actually useful in the context of Liver Disease. In this sense, Data Exploration gave us some hints: TB, IB, Alkphos, Sgpt, A/G Ratio (features that have been selected) seems have distinguishable ranges where the Target Variable assumes a certain value. This, united with results obtained from classification, shows how they are actually correlated with the Liver Disease.

If we take into consideration Accuracy and F1-score, the model performs better on Male records. So the hypothesis of the research question might be true. However, to fully investigate such question and being able to reach meaningful results, more data is needed. Here we used the same model trained on both Gender. A single model should be build for each Gender, using the same biochemical markers. Maybe, only at that point we would have answers that can address this hypotetical difference.
